revision.text:
The '''Building Information Modelling ([[Building information modeling|BIM]]) Task Group''' is a [[UK Government]]-funded group, managed through the [[Cabinet Office]], created in 2011 (and holding its first meeting in May 2011) and chaired by [[Mark Bew]]. It was founded to "drive adoption of BIM across government" in support of the ''Government Construction Strategy''.<ref name=GCS>Cabinet Office (2011) ''[https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/61152/Government-Construction-Strategy_0.pdf Government Construction Strategy]''. Accessed: 2 September 2014.</ref> It aimed to strengthen the public sector’s capabilities in BIM implementation to that all central government departments can adopt, as a minimum, collaborative 'Level 2' BIM by 2016.
The core BIM task force, to which companies seconded employees, identified four work streams, each led by a core team member: stakeholder and media engagement, delivery and productivity, commercial and legal, and training and academia.<ref>BIM Task Group, ''[http://www.bimtaskgroup.org/work-streams-wps/ Work streams and work packages]''. Accessed 2 September 2014.</ref> Working parties were established to focus on particular areas including: training and education, [[COBie]] data set requirements, Plan of Works, software vendors (the BIM Technologies Alliance), contractors ([[UK Contractors Group]], now superseded by [[Build UK]]), and materials and products suppliers ([[Construction Products Association]]).<ref>BIM Task Group, ''[http://www.bimtaskgroup.org/working-parties/ Working Parties]''. Accessed 2 September 2014.</ref>
In early 2014, it was announced that the BIM Task Group would be wound down during 2015, with a "managed handover" during 2015 to a newly created "legacy group", though there was speculation that the group's life might be extended to help achieve a new BIM Level 3 target.<ref name=Withers>{{cite news|last1=Withers|first1=Ian|title=Concern over plans to wind down BIM Task Group|url=http://www.building.co.uk/concern-over-plans-to-wind-down-bim-task-group/5068515.article|accessdate=2 September 2014|work=Building|publisher=UBM|date=16 May 2014}}</ref><ref name=Clarkson>{{cite news|last1=Clarkson|first1=Graham|title=Are we ready to manage without the BIM Task Group?|url=http://www.construction-manager.co.uk/comment/are-we-ready-manage-without-bim-task-group/|accessdate=2 September 2014|work=Construction Manager|publisher=Atom Publishing|date=30 May 2014}}</ref>
In October 2016, an updated BIM Task Group delivering the February 2015 ''Digital Built Britain'' strategy was announced at the [[Institution of Civil Engineers]] BIM 2016 Conference in a keynote speech by Mark Bew.<ref>Innovate UK, ''[https://www.gov.uk/government/news/launch-of-digital-built-britain Launch of Digital Built Britain]''. Accessed 19 October 2016.</ref><ref>BIMPlus, ''[http://www.bimplus.co.uk/news/digital-built-britain-officially-launched/ Digital Built Britain officially launched]''. Accessed 19 October 2016.</ref><ref>Infrastructure Intelligence, ''[http://www.infrastructure-intelligence.com/article/oct-2016/digital-built-britain-launches-next-phase-constructions-digitisation Digital Built Britain launches next phase of construction's digitisation ]''. Accessed 19 October 2016.</ref>
