{{Infobox writer | name = Forrest Pritchard | embed = | honorific_prefix = | honorific_suffix = | image = Eb752f895229ef535c41e7433a7aa19b-2cddec953d6970787740c1dcb244ae9d.jpg | image_size = | image_upright = | alt = | caption = Pritchard lecturing in Ft. Wayne, IN | native_name = | native_name_lang = | pseudonym = | birth_name = Forrest Pritchard | birth_date = June 1, 1974 | birth_place = | death_date = <!-- {{Death date and age|YYYY|MM|DD|YYYY|MM|DD}} --> | death_place = | resting_place = | occupation = | language = | nationality = | citizenship = | education = BA English, BS Geology | alma_mater = [[College of William & Mary]] | period = | genre = <!-- or: | genres = --> | subject = | movement = | notableworks = Gaining Ground, Growing Tomorrow, Start Your Farm | spouse = <!-- or: | spouses = --> | partner = <!-- or: | partners = --> | children = | relatives = | awards = | signature = | signature_alt = | years_active = | module = | website = {{URL|www.forrestpritchard.com}} | portaldisp = <!-- "on", "yes", "true", etc; or omit --> }}
'''Forrest Pritchard''' (born June 1, 1974) is a ''New York Times'' bestselling author<ref name="nyt">{{cite web|url=https://www.nytimes.com/best-sellers-books/2015-06-14/e-book-nonfiction/list.html?date=2015-06-14&category=e-book-nonfiction&pagewanted=print | title=E-Book Nonfiction | date=14 June 2015 | accessdate=27 May 2016}}</ref> and seventh generation sustainable farmer, living at [[Smithfield Farm]] in Berryville, Virginia, United States. He is a graduate of [[Episcopal High School (Alexandria, Virginia)|Episcopal High School]] and [[College of William & Mary|The College of William and Mary]], where he won the Academy of American Poets prize in 1996.<ref>https://wmalumni.com/content/tcwm/alumni/get-informed/gale/2016/growing-tomorrow.html</ref> His farm, called Smith Meadows,<ref>[http://smithmeadows.com Smith Meadows]</ref> was one of the first "grass-finished" farms in the country,<ref>http://modernfarmer.com/2013/07/gaining-ground-qa-with-forrest-pritchard/</ref> and sells at farmers' markets in the Washington, DC area. His books include the ''New York Times'' bestseller ''Gaining Ground, A Story of Farmers' Markets, Local Food and Saving the Family Farm'' (Lyons, 2013, {{ISBN|9780762787258}}, no. 19 in E-books non-fiction)<ref name="nyt" /> named a top read by NPR<ref>http://www.splendidtable.org/story/6-food-books-for-summer-reading</ref> and Publishers Weekly,<ref>http://best-books.publishersweekly.com/pw/best-books/summer-reads-2013/nonfiction#book/book-7</ref> and ''Growing Tomorrow: Behind The Scenes With 18 Sustainable Farmers Who Are Changing The Way We Eat'' (with Molly Peterson, The Experiment, 2015 {{ISBN|9781615192847}}).
