{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2016}} {{Infobox Government agency |agency_name = Ministry of Oil |type = Ministerial Department |logo = |logo_width = |logo_caption = |seal = |seal_width = |seal_caption = |formed = {{start date and age|1975|4|1|df=yes}} |dissolved = |superseding = |jurisdiction =[[Kuwait]] |headquarters = [[Kuwait City]] |employees = |budget = |minister1_name = [[Essam Abdulmohsen Al Marzooq]] |minister1_pfo = Minister of Oil, Electricity and Water |child1_agency = [[Kuwait Petroleum Corporation|Kuwait Petroleum Corporation (KPC)]] |child2_agency = |child3_agency = |website = [http://www.moo.gov.kw Official website] |footnotes = }}
The '''Ministry of Oil''' is one of [[Government of Kuwait|the governmental bodies]] of [[Kuwait]] and part of [[Cabinet of Kuwait|the cabinet]].
==History and profile== The production and export of oil in Kuwait were among the responsibilities of Kuwait's finance department until 1962 when the department was reorganized under the name of the ministry of finance and oil.<ref name=winfre>{{cite book|title=Kuwait: Prospect and Reality|year=1972|publisher=Allen & Unwin|location=London|url=https://www.questia.com/read/10343848/kuwait-prospect-and-reality|author=H. V. F. Winstone|author2=Zahra Freeth|accessdate=21 December 2013}}{{Subscription required|via=Questia}}</ref> Then the body was renamed as the ministry of finance and economy and dealt with oil-related policies until April 1975 when the ministry of oil was established.<ref name=bhis>{{cite web|title=Brief History|url=http://www.moo.gov.kw/About-Us/Brief-History.aspx|work=Ministry of Oil|accessdate=24 November 2013}}</ref> The ministry was established to protect the state’s natural resources along with two other major public bodies, namely the [[Supreme Petroleum Council (Kuwait)|Supreme Petroleum Council]] and the [[Kuwait Petroleum Corporation]].<ref name=opec>{{cite journal|title=A review of upstream development policies in Kuwait|journal=OPEC Review|date=December 2004|volume=28|issue=4|url=http://onlinelibrary.wiley.com/doi/10.1111/j.0277-0180.2004.00138.x/pdf|accessdate=30 December 2013|author=Abdulaziz E. Al Attar|doi=10.1111/j.0277-0180.2004.00138.x}}</ref> The ministry is headquartered in [[Kuwait City]].<ref name=ei>[http://en.openei.org/wiki/State_of_Kuwait_Ministry_of_Oil State of Kuwait Ministry of Oil] ''OpenEI'' Retrieved 24 November 2013</ref>
In 1986 the ministry was separated from the [[Ministry of Finance (Kuwait)|Ministry of Finance]].<ref name=opec/> At the same time on 12 August 1986 the mission of the ministry was refined and includes the following: Protecting, exploiting and developing the petroleum resources, and raising the share of petroleum in the national income and securing the safety of workers, environment and structures.<ref name=ei/> The ministry was reorganized as part of the Ministry of Energy in 2003.<ref name=opec/> Following this reorganization, energy policy of the country is overseen by the ministry.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kuwait|url=http://www.eia.gov/COUNTRIES/cab.cfm?fips=KU|work=US Energy Information Administration|accessdate=24 November 2013}}</ref> The [[Kuwait Petroleum Corporation]] is the major state-run body governed by the ministry.<ref>{{cite web|title=Kuwait Petroleum Corporation (KPC)|url=http://www.gulfoilandgas.com/webpro1/prod1/Partner.asp?sid=6210|work=Gulf Oil and Gas|accessdate=24 November 2013}}</ref>
==Ministers and functions== The minister of oil is the major advisor to the [[Amir of Kuwait]].<ref>{{cite book|title=The Changing Dynamics of Energy in the Middle East|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=fqnlNP0h29MC&pg=PA261|accessdate=30 December 2013|date=1 October 2006|publisher=Greenwood Publishing Group|isbn=978-0-313-08364-8|page=261}}</ref> The minister is also a member of the Supreme Petroleum Council.{{cn|date=October 2015}}
From 1978 to June 1990 Ali Khalifa Al Sabah was the minister of oil.<ref>{{cite news|title=Profile: Shaikh Ali Khalifa|url=http://www.highbeam.com/doc/1G1-42091862.html|accessdate=21 December 2013|work=APS Review Downstream Trends|date=20 May 1991}}{{Subscription required|via=HighBeam}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|author=Marc Duvoisin|title=Kuwaiti Oil Minister Downplays Iran's Naval Threat|url=http://articles.philly.com/1987-06-23/news/26184645_1_naval-protection-tankers-kuwaiti-oil|accessdate=10 September 2014|work=Philly|date=23 June 1987}}</ref> [[Saud Nasser Al-Saud Al-Sabah|Saud Nasser Al Sabah]] served in the post between 1998 and 2000.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kuwait former oil minister dies – royal court|url=http://newsinfo.inquirer.net/132401/kuwait-former-oil-minister-dies-%E2%80%93-royal-court|accessdate=10 September 2014|work=Inquirer|agency=AFP|date=22 January 2012}}</ref> He resigned from the post in June 2000 due to an explosion that killed five workers at three oil refineries.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kuwait oil minister resigns in wake of explosion|url=http://lubbockonline.com/stories/062700/bus_062700005.shtml|accessdate=10 September 2014|work=Lubbock Avalanche Journal|agency=AP|date=27 June 2000}}</ref> Adel Al Subaih served as oil minister until February 2002 when he resigned from the post.<ref name=erg>{{cite news|title=Kuwaiti oil minister resigns|url=https://news.google.com/newspapers?nid=1310&dat=20020211&id=bkxWAAAAIBAJ&sjid=9OsDAAAAIBAJ&pg=4228,2901021|accessdate=10 September 2014|work=Eugene Register-Guard|date=11 February 2002}}</ref> He was replaced by [[Ahmed Al-Fahad Al-Ahmed Al-Sabah|Ahmed Fahd Al Sabah]] as oil minister.<ref name=erg/>
The ministry was headed by five different officials between February 2006 and February 2009.<ref name=pipe/> In late 2007 Bader Mishari Al Humaidhi was appointed oil minister.<ref name=Hil2008>{{cite book|author=Joseph Hilyard|title=2008 International Petroleum Encyclopedia|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=S_Upmb8NZkAC&pg=PA184|accessdate=30 December 2013|date=1 July 2008|publisher=PennWell Books|isbn=978-1-59370-164-2|page=184}}</ref> However, he resigned from office only eight days after his appointment due to harsh criticisms of the members of the [[Parliament of Kuwait|Kuwaiti parliament]].<ref name=Hil2008/> Mohammad Al Olaim was the oil minister until his resignation in November 2008.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kuwait appoints new permanent oil minister|url=http://www.pipelineme.com/news/regional-news/2009/12/kuwait-appoints-new-permanent-oil-minister/|accessdate=24 November 2013|work=Pipeline Magazine|date=10 December 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202223708/http://www.pipelineme.com/news/regional-news/2009/12/kuwait-appoints-new-permanent-oil-minister/|archivedate=2 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> Abdulmohsen Al Madaj also served as Kuwaiti oil minister.<ref name=ash/>
From February 2009 to May 2011 [[Ahmad Al Abdullah Al Sabah]] served as the minister of oil.<ref name=pipe>{{cite news|title=Kuwait appoints new permanent oil minister|url=http://www.pipelineme.com/news/regional-news/2009/12/kuwait-appoints-new-permanent-oil-minister/|accessdate=24 November 2013|work=Pipeline Magazine|date=10 December 2009|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131202223708/http://www.pipelineme.com/news/regional-news/2009/12/kuwait-appoints-new-permanent-oil-minister/|archivedate=2 December 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Kuwait's new cabinet sworn in, oil minister replaced|url=http://english.peopledaily.com.cn/90001/90777/90854/7373590.html|accessdate=24 November 2013|work=People's Daily Online|date=9 May 2011}}</ref> Mohammad Al Busairi was the oil minister from May 2011 to February 2012.<ref name=woil/> [[Hani Abdulaziz Al Hussein|Hani Hussein]] was named the oil minister in a cabinet reshuffle in February 2012.<ref name=woil>{{cite news|title=Kuwait replaces oil minister with ex-KPC head|url=http://www.worldoil.com/Kuwait_replaces_oil_minister_with_ex_KPC_head.html|accessdate=24 November 2013|work=World Oil|date=14 February 2012|author=Summer Said|location=Kuwait City}}</ref> Hussein resigned from office on 26 May 2013 due to tensions with members of the Kuwaiti parliament.<ref>{{cite news|title=Kuwaiti oil minister’s resignation: What happened?|url=http://www.aawsat.net/2013/05/article55303320|accessdate=24 November 2013|newspaper=Asharq Alawsat|date=27 May 2013|deadurl=yes|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20131106113201/http://www.aawsat.net/2013/05/article55303320|archivedate=6 November 2013|df=dmy-all}}</ref> [[Mustafa Jassem Al-Shamali|Mustafa Jassem Al Shamali]] served as oil minister from 4 August 2013<ref>{{cite web|title=Curriculum Vitae|url=http://www.moo.gov.kw/Special-Pages/CV-Minister.aspx|work=Kuwait Ministry of Oil|accessdate=24 November 2013}}</ref> to January 2014, when [[Ali al-Omair]] replaced him in the post<ref name=ash>{{cite news|title=Kuwait cabinet reshuffle brings seven new faces|url=http://www.aawsat.net/2014/01/article55326744|accessdate=10 September 2014|work=Asharq Al Awsat|date=7 January 2014|location=London}}</ref> and became the ninth oil minister since 2004.<ref>{{cite news|author=Fiona MacDonald|title=Kuwait PM Shuffles Cabinet, Appoints New Finance, Oil Ministers|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2014-01-06/kuwait-pm-shuffles-cabinet-appoints-new-finance-oil-ministers.html|accessdate=10 September 2014|work=Bloomberg|date=6 January 2014}}</ref> In November 2015, Al-Omair was replaced by [[Anas Khalid Al Saleh]] as acting oil minister.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/us-kuwait-oil-idUSKBN0TI0CL20151129 |title=Kuwait names new acting oil minister; policy change not expected |agency=Reuters |date=29 November 2015 |accessdate=8 March 2016}}</ref>
